{"id": "fm1cgf", "title": "Junk corporate bonds and typically stable municipal bonds are failing", "selftext": "High yield corporate bonds are under tremendous stress. Apparently 86% of these bonds composing some of America\u2019s top companies are \u201cunder stress\u201d. Exxon for instance dropped from AAA to AA debt rating. \n\n\nhttps://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-bad-is-the-corporate-bond-carnage-highly-rated-us-companies-are-having-their-worst-month-on-record-2020-03-19\n\nOn the other hand, the traditionally very stable municipal bonds are also now creaking. To clarify these are the bonds related to municipal functioning and are very diverse composing things from mall loans to public transit loans. Considering the closure of California and NY, and the many more states to come (in addition to jobless claims), municipalities are going to take an incredible damage. That\u2019s why the Feds decided this week to start buying municipal bonds, something that wasn\u2019t even done in 2008. \n\n\nhttps://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-19/muni-bond-investors-yank-a-record-12-billion-from-mutual-funds\n\nShorting both these in the form of ETFs might be a nice play provided the strike is about 1-3 months away. It may not have the flash of SPY, but this is not a question of if but when. \n\nTl;dr: \n\nHYG 64p 4/24\nMUB 101p 5/15\n\nThey have low volumes currently but will inevitably pick up when the job loss and credit default reports kick in.", "created_utc": 1584733437.0, "permalink": "/r/wallstreetbets/comments/fm1cgf/junk_corporate_bonds_and_typically_stable/", "is_self": true}